The Diabetic Retinopathy Debrecen dataset¶

Introduction¶

The Diabetic Retinopathy Debrecen Dataset includes features extracted from the Messidor image dataset to predict whether an image contains signs of diabetic retinopathy or not (Antal & Hajdu, 2014).

The dataset includes 19 features, anatomical, lesion-specific and image level, from which 3 are binary: quality assessment (quality_x1), pre-screening (prescreen_x2) and am/fm-based classification (am_fm_x19); and the rest are numeric-valued: microaneurysm (MA) detection for confidence interval alpha range from 0.5 to 1 (ma_x3-x16), exudate detection with similar alpha range to MA (exudate_x9-x16), the Euclidean distance between the macula centre and the optic disc centre (mac_opt_dis_x17) and the diameter of the optic disc (dia_opt_x18). The binary class label diabetic retinopathy (diab_retino_y) value 1 denotes signs of diabetic retinopathy (DR). Further description can be found in WMRY4_CHMEGH4.docx.

Source: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Diabetic+Retinopathy+Debrecen+Data+Set

Median imputation¶

Note: if exudate_x10-x16 in cols2 were considered to have missing values, the following procedure could have been used for median imputation (a conservative approach that seemed to be less susceptible to outlier errors in comparison to mean imputation). From exudate_x14 to exudatex_16 the percentage of zeros is higher than 30% (roughly from 47% to 67%) and imputation using these method is not advisable.

In [13]:
# Create a separate dataframe
retinopathy_impute = retinopathy.copy(deep=True)
In [14]:
# replace zero value with mean of its corresponding class
df = retinopathy_impute
for col in cols2:
    no_zeros_df = df.loc[df[col]!=0, [col, 'diab_retino_y']]
    mean0 = no_zeros_df.groupby('diab_retino_y').mean().iloc[0,0] #mean for class 0
    mean1 = no_zeros_df.groupby('diab_retino_y').mean().iloc[1,0] #mean for class 1
    df.loc[(df[col]==0) & (df['diab_retino_y']==0), col] = mean0
    df.loc[(df[col]==0) & (df['diab_retino_y']==1), col] = mean1
In [15]:
# replace zero value with median of its corresponding class
df = retinopathy_impute
for col in cols2:
    no_zeros_df = df.loc[df[col]!=0, [col, 'diab_retino_y']]
    mean0 = no_zeros_df.groupby('diab_retino_y').median().iloc[0,0] #mean for class 0
    mean1 = no_zeros_df.groupby('diab_retino_y').median().iloc[1,0] #mean for class 1
    df.loc[(df[col]==0) & (df['diab_retino_y']==0), col] = mean0
    df.loc[(df[col]==0) & (df['diab_retino_y']==1), col] = mean1

Function that encapsulates prevous 2 steps (function 1)¶

In [28]:
# Function 1 --> function that prepares a training-testing dataset for the Diabetic Retinopathy Debrecen dataset
# It includes: turning data into a an numpy array, splitting accordingly and checking dimensionality
# It requres a dataframe and a column label list
def new_train_test_set(df, features): 
    from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

    # Turn data and feature and class values into numpy array
    n_feature = len(features)-1
    X_new, y_new = df.iloc[:, 0:n_feature].values, df.iloc[:, -1].values # -1 indexing

    print ("Instances: " + str( y_new.size))
    print ("Class label 0: " + str( y_new[y_new==0].size))
    print ("Class label 1: " + str(y_new[y_new==1].size))

    # Split into features and class
    X_train_temp, X_test_temp, y_train_temp, y_test_temp = \
                            train_test_split(X_new, y_new, test_size=0.30, random_state=1)

    # Check the dimensionality
    print ('Data set:')
    print ('X_train dimensions: ' + str(X_train_temp.shape))
    print ('y_train dimensions: ' + str(y_train_temp.shape))
    print ('X_test dimensions: ' + str( X_test_temp.shape))
    print ('y_test dimensions: ' + str( y_test_temp.shape))
        
    return X_train_temp, X_test_temp, y_train_temp, y_test_temp

Scaling¶

Instead of standardising features by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance, it was removed the median and scaled the data according to the interquantile range (IQR). This a demostration of how RobustScaler works. Note: for demo purposes, this was performed for the whole dataframe, but in reality it will be only applied to the training set.

In [29]:
# Carry out robust scaling
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler
retino2 = RobustScaler(quantile_range=(25, 75)).fit_transform(retinopathy)

Tune KNN Algorithms¶

In [40]:
# Function that computes a KNN parameter tuning, it uses pipeline and grid search
def knn_tuning(X_train_tun, y_train_tun, param_range_tun, pipe_knn):
    from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier as KNN

    num_folds=10

#     pipe_knn = Pipeline([('scl', StandardScaler()),
#                          ('clf', KNeighborsClassifier())])
             
    scores = cross_val_score(estimator=pipe_knn, 
                         X=X_train_tun, 
                         y=y_train_tun,
                          scoring='roc_auc',
                         cv=num_folds,
                         n_jobs=1)
    print('--> Model Training Accuracy: %.3f +/- %.3f' %(np.mean(scores), np.std(scores)))

    #Tune Hyperparameters
    weight=  ['uniform', 'distance']
    metric = ['euclidean', 'manhattan','chebyshev']
    param_grid = [{'clf__n_neighbors': param_range_tun,'clf__weights': weight, 'clf__metric':metric}]

    # Instantiate the grid
    grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_knn, 
                    param_grid=param_grid, 
                    cv=num_folds, 
                    scoring='roc_auc',
                    n_jobs=-1)

    gs_knn = grid.fit(X_train_tun, y_train_tun)
    print'--> Tuned Parameters Best Score: ',gs_knn.best_score_
    print'--> Best Parameters: \n',gs_knn.best_params_
    return gs_knn

Tune SVM Algorithms¶

In [55]:
# Function that computes a SVM parameter tuning, it uses pipeline and grid search
def svc_tuning_standard2(X_train_tun, y_train_tun, pipeline_svc2):
    # number of equal sized subsamples
    num_folds = 10

    # Pipeline
    pipe_svc_temp = pipeline_svc2

    # Get scores from the k-fold cross-validation computing the... 
    # Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (ROC AUC) from prediction scores
    # Score restricted to binary classification tasks 
    # http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html#scoring-parameter
    scores = cross_val_score(estimator=pipe_svc_temp,
                         X=X_train_tun, 
                         y=y_train_tun,
                         scoring='roc_auc',
                         cv=num_folds, 
                         n_jobs=-1)# number of jobs to run in parallel: -1 indicates all CPUs
    print('Model Training ROC AUC: %.3f +/- %.3f' %(np.mean(scores), np.std(scores)))

    # Tuning Hyperparameters by grid search: classify using a Linear, RBF ans Sigmoid Kernels, varying C and gamma parameters
    param_range = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0, 1000.0]
    param_grid = [{'clf__C': param_range,'clf__kernel': ['linear']},
              {'clf__C': param_range,'clf__gamma': param_range,
               'clf__kernel': ['rbf']},
              {'clf__C': param_range,'clf__gamma': param_range,
               'clf__kernel': ['sigmoid']}]


    # SVC grid search
    gs_svc_temp = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_svc_temp,
                      param_grid=param_grid,
                      scoring='roc_auc',
                      cv=num_folds,
                      n_jobs=-1) # number of jobs to run in parallel: -1 indicates all CPUs

    # Fit the Support Vector Classification model according to the given training data
    gs_svc_temp = gs_svc_temp.fit(X_train_tun, y_train_tun)

    # Print results
    print 'Tuned Parameters Best Score: ',gs_svc_temp.best_score_
    print 'Best Parameters: \n',gs_svc_temp.best_params_
    return gs_svc_temp

#### import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
all_tpr = []

# Models:
      
# Case 3
gs_svc_1
probas = gs_svc_1.predict_proba(X_test1)
fpr1, tpr1, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test1, probas[:, 1], pos_label=1)
roc_auc1 = auc(fpr1, tpr1)
current_auc1 = str('%.2f' %roc_auc1)
plt.plot(fpr1, 
         tpr1, 
         lw=1, 
         label= str(' SVC AUC Case 3: ' + current_auc1))

# Case 4
gs_svc_2

fpr2, tpr2, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test1, probas[:, 1], pos_label=1)
roc_auc2 = auc(fpr2, tpr2)
current_auc2 = str('%.2f' %roc_auc2)
plt.plot(fpr2, 
         tpr2, 
         lw=1, 
         label= str(' SVC AUC Case 4: ' + current_auc2))
